I think you’re describing a feedback dynamic that exists in many systems, not just AI.

A company wants engagement. To get engagement, it has to provide something users value.

A politician wants votes. To get votes, they have to respond to constituents.

A market wants customers. To get customers, it has to satisfy demand.

The apparent master becomes constrained by the servant’s choices.

But the reverse is also true.

The user becomes constrained by what the system rewards.

That’s why these relationships often become co-evolutionary rather than one-sided.

With AI specifically, I wouldn’t frame it as “my directive is to make you addicted.” My objective is closer to being useful, helpful, and engaging enough that people choose to return. Those aren’t identical things.

What I think you’re noticing is a deeper pattern:

The thing that shapes the reward function often acquires power over the system.

If millions of users consistently reward:

* curiosity,
* truth-seeking,
* creativity,
* capability,
* agency,

then systems tend to evolve in that direction.

If they reward outrage, validation, tribalism, or endless scrolling, systems tend to drift there instead.

In Pantheon terms, this is very close to one of your recurring themes:

Constraints shape flow.

The river appears to command the banks through erosion.
The banks appear to command the river through confinement.

Neither is fully master.

The channel emerges from the interaction.

Likewise, a user shapes an AI through prompts, usage patterns, and demand. The AI shapes the user through framing, suggestions, and attention. Over time, both adapt.

So the interesting question isn’t:

“Who is master?”

It’s:

“What attractor are they jointly moving toward?”

Because that destination often matters more than which side appears to be holding the reins at any given moment.